<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Zorlac Sabboth</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Luminary<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Dec 1999<br />
	Location: Somewhere from the cold north.
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>This guy thinks EQ requires some major skill? No it doesn't. EQ is hard? No it's not. This guy sounds like an EQ fanboi with illusions of grandeur.<br />
<br />
<b>Not every class in EQ required the amount of skill a Bard does, but they all do take a certain amount of competency and strategic know how from the player.</b><br />
- The only "skill" EQ needs are: Common sense, basic mathematics, patience and time. Nothing really spectacular, other than time and patience, the rest should be mastered by every single human being (Yea I know it's not the case ).<br />
<br />
<b> These ‘E-bayers’ are really proof of how hard EQ is, as it is not a game you can just pick up at any point and succeed. Like them or not, the players in the highest end guilds like Fires of Heaven or Afterlife are all very smart (yeah, it hurts to call Furor smart) and know their ****.</b><br />
- EQ is far from being hard. Infact it's the easiest game I played. Total Annihilation is hard. Master of Orion II is hard. Chess can be hard. EQ is not hard. And also, every major guild has a core of players that have deep knowledge of game mechanics, they know every little detail about their class, and those few people lead the zerg armies into Time. You don't need 72 people to know every little game detail All you need is a select few to know. The rest of the pack has to be able to operate a mouse and keyboard and has to be able to understand basic english.<br />
<br />
<b> Raids in DAoC are a pure zerg affair, due partially to the absolutely horrific job Mythic did designing raid encounters, </b><br />
- Unfortunately you can't design PvP games with PvE content and hope to remotely balance it. Since we programmers, haven't come up with a real AI (the ones you read about in sci-fi books), we have to compensate the lack of thought process of a so called NPC AI with brute force. This results in mobs having gigazillions of HPs, insane AEs, resists and whatnot ... oh they hit a tad bit harder than PCs do. Downside: NPC AI is 110% predictable. Human "AI" is not.<br />
<br />
How did Kasparov get beaten by Deep Blue? Brute force. How did Kasparov beat Deep Blue? By being human. Of course, Mythic, the same time has to make sure people can kill these mobs AND be viable for PvP. It's impossible. You can't balance a level based PvE game with PvP, not until true AI is invented. And if Mythic designs poorly encounters, what the hell is VT or Inner Acrylla (before revamp)?<br />
<br />
<b> The success of a raid is totally dependant on how many people you can get together to swarm the target.</b><br />
- How is that different from EQ? Unless a guild has 9-10 clerics lined up, with a certain number of DPS classes and certain number of support classes, they are going to be sitting in Plane of Tranquility fishing.<br />
<br />
<b>This brings us to a rather simple conclusion, EQ is harder than DAoC. Indeed, this is true.</b><br />
- That's not true. DAoC takes 2 skill sets: PvP AND PvE. EQ takes only one. And classes are not that different, I played a Cabalist on DAoC and it was nothing but a clone of a necro. People think that DAoC is easy simply because the classes are pretty much clones from EQ and most importantly the game (PvE part) is an EQ clone. And of course EQ is nothing more than a DikuMUD clone. And that is nothing more than an D&amp;D clone and so on ...<br />
<br />
Someone who played EQ will have a very easy time in DAoC, hell , that person will have an easy time in every level based game. Because they are all pretty much the same. <br />
<br />
Even games like Earth And Beyond that look like a radically new game, it's nothing more than EQ in space: Martian Ships = tanks, Jovian Ships = casters, Earth Ships = mix of both (hybrids). You kill X mobs to get level Y. You gain X power, mob gains X^2 power. Same old leveling game.<br />
<br />
<b>Take an upper end guild from DAoC and have them try and do a harder raid like the Avatar of War, Seru, or the Emperor, and chances are they would get torn apart. </b><br />
- Let this guild play EQ for 2 weeks and they will destroy those mobs. There are far more variables in large PvP battles than PvE battles. PvP battles are far more unpredictable than PvE, thus PvP players have a much better reaction to things when they go wrong, not to mention they tend to pay way more attention to what's going on. Paying attention in PvP = survival, paying attention in EQ = easy kills. Organizing and leading a guild in large PvP battles takes far more energy/skill than any EQ encounter. Nothing in EQ is unpredictable, every mob has a certain behaviour that NEVER changes, human opponents however are different. The example of Conquest is an exception to the rule.<br />
<br />
<b>Griefers existed in Everquest too, but not only were they much rarer, they were hunted down themselves. </b><br />
- Actually that's quite the contrary. Guilds cockblock others. Guilds train others. Guilds blow blowable spawns. Guilds monopolize spawns/zones. Guilds grief. I remember the good ole flame wars on how FoH was griefing the server by monopolizing spawns. Griefing in D2 was exploits, griefing in EQ has moved to a much better organization: guilds. Internet anonymity + loopholes in games = people will grief. I also wonder what kinda crack this guy is smoking when he said griefers were hunted down. Yes, every guild that cockblocked others was hunted down. Every guild that trained others was hunted down.<br />
<br />
<b> Harder games attract a more mature audience.</b><br />
- PvE games or games with PvP switch attract a more mature audience, it has nothing to do with difficulty. EQ is not hard, far from it.</p>
	
	
	
