<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>mcroc</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Luminary<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Sep 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Yeah I have to agree with the majority of posters here Everquest isn't hard. IT DOES have a steep learning curve to anyone that joins the game and has not played a mmorpg before.<br />
<br />
Skill wise? Hmm I don't really call it skill. Or maybe there is but its not obvious which skills.<br />
<br />
Hmm, there are differences intially I would guess of effective managing. Ie combining many roles and choosing which are the best. These verg more towards the same at later levels with usage of community boards etc. In a shamans case in a grouping situation it is balancing debuffing, slowing and healing. If this is considered skill then its marginalized by the lack of variety to test these skills and by the number of times you have to perform these skills.<br />
<br />
Raiding, there is not much skill either really. There are tactics which essentially revolve around a MT and a cleric chealing them. (Obviously there are exceptions, like Coirnav or Rathe.) Raiding requires a lot of organization, and so this could be considered a skill whoever is organizing. (and what elements) There is little in the way of skill on the individual level. There are styles and roles which individuals can differ in.<br />
<br />
So in short I think it is hard to agree with the article that Everquest possesses more skill than most mmorpgs. It does have elements of organization and management skills but these are marginalized by the number of times you have to do them.<br />
<br />
Everquests success in a lot of ways is getting people together to do things. And having a interdepedent organization. Ie all the best abilities are divided up between everyone and we have to effectively rely on people doing their jobs in groups.<br />
<br />
At the end of the day though,  my reasons for playing everquest never revolved around skills. It revolved around immersiveness, interacting and discovering.(+Character Advancement) Elements which have dwindled away as everquest has progressed.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
		<div class="smallfont"><a href="report.php?s=cce877e6623a18e61cf243d19379fb11&amp;postid=223088">Report Post</a> | IP: <a href="postings.php?s=cce877e6623a18e61cf243d19379fb11&amp;do=getip&postid=223088">Logged</a></div>
	
